beat 8.x might create incompatible index formats or have compatibility issues with the older ES output.\n\nNow I'm planning out the full deployment: first I'll set up the monitoring cluster itself, then create adapted ConfigMaps for metricbeat and filebeat that work with ES 8.11.1 as the source (no TLS, no auth) while shipping to the monitoring cluster.\n\nWriting ConfigMap definitions...\n\nThe tricky part is that the existing orphaned pods have specific volume configurations including the s3 plugin directory, TLS certificates, and file-realm volumes, but the new StatefulSet needs to maintain compatibility with those while adding the sidecar containers that share the logs volume.\n\nWhen I create the StatefulSet with matching labels and names, the controller will adopt those existing pods and perform a rolling update since I'm using the RollingUpdate strategy, which means it'll gradually replace them with the new spec rather than deleting them all at once.\n\nNow I'm building the StatefulSet definition that will use the current ES 8.11.1 image, keep the existing configmap reference, add metricbeat and filebeat sidecars, set up a shared logs volume between ES and filebeat, and include the es-logs emptyDir. I also need to preserve the existing initContainers like the S3 plugin installer and permissions fixer.\n\nLooking at the current pod's volume mounts to understand what needs to be carried over...\n\nActually, rather than trying to replicate the exact pod spec with all its secrets and config maps, I should take a simpler approach. Since these pods are orphaned and can't be patched directly, I'll create a new StatefulSet that will handle the rollout properly.\n\nI need to see the complete volumes section from the current pod YAML to understand all the volume definitions, not just the volume mounts. Let me fetch the rest of that pod spec.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tok